1
00:00:56,891 --> 00:00:58,483
[CASHIER SPEAKS FRENCH]

2
00:00:59,611 --> 00:01:00,839
Where are you going?

3
00:01:01,011 --> 00:01:05,880
MAN ON PA: The 2: 15 to Mont Laurier
will be loading at gate number 10.

4
00:01:11,171 --> 00:01:13,207
One ticket, please. Mont Laurier.

5
00:01:18,971 --> 00:01:22,407
Do you mind? The guy in the back,
he won't stop snoring.

6
00:01:24,211 --> 00:01:26,406
No. Sure.

7
00:01:28,491 --> 00:01:30,129
I'm Matt.

8
00:01:30,731 --> 00:01:32,926
- I'm Martin.
- Hey, Martin. Nice to meet you.

9
00:01:33,091 --> 00:01:35,844
- Nice to meet you.
- Where you headed to?

10
00:01:36,331 --> 00:01:38,128
Just as far away as I can get.

11
00:01:39,251 --> 00:01:41,321
Well, I'll drink to that, brother.

12
00:01:47,531 --> 00:01:49,169
Cheers.

13
00:01:54,291 --> 00:01:56,759
[ENGINE BACKFIRES]

14
00:01:59,611 --> 00:02:03,126
DRIVER: I think we got a little
engine trouble here, folks. Just sit tight.

15
00:02:03,291 --> 00:02:06,089
Man! You know, the same thing
happened in St. Lawrence.

16
00:02:06,331 --> 00:02:08,799
We had to sit tight for nearly eight hours.

17
00:02:08,971 --> 00:02:12,680
Hell, this sucks. This totally sucks.

18
00:02:15,051 --> 00:02:17,440
MAN: Three hundred and eighty-five
dollars. Cash only.

19
00:02:17,611 --> 00:02:19,363
All I got is my dad's credit card.

20
00:02:20,651 --> 00:02:22,403
You can't read?

21
00:02:22,691 --> 00:02:24,522
Cash only.

22
00:02:26,251 --> 00:02:30,529
- You have a license?
- I had one. They took it away, though.

23
00:02:30,811 --> 00:02:32,688
Looks like you're driving.

24
00:02:44,971 --> 00:02:47,360
[SCREAMING]

25
00:02:51,971 --> 00:02:53,450
MATT:
See that?

26
00:02:57,091 --> 00:02:58,240
Fake.

27
00:02:58,411 --> 00:03:00,402
- What happened?
- Courtesy of my stepdad.

28
00:03:00,571 --> 00:03:03,847
Hit me so hard I flew across the kitchen,
dented the Sheetrock.

29
00:03:04,011 --> 00:03:05,603
My mom watched the whole thing.

30
00:03:05,771 --> 00:03:08,239
- Why?
- Why does he do half the things he does?

31
00:03:08,411 --> 00:03:11,801
Fucking psycho,
200 pounds of worthless grease.

32
00:03:12,011 --> 00:03:13,842
But I got him back.

33
00:03:14,091 --> 00:03:15,240
What? You popped him?

34
00:03:15,411 --> 00:03:19,290
Got me a tour of hell, though. Had me
in military school by the next morning.

35
00:03:19,451 --> 00:03:22,090
But I don't believe in following
people's rules, man.

36
00:03:22,251 --> 00:03:25,960
Fuck people, fuck their rules. That's
why I jumped the wall two days ago.

37
00:03:26,131 --> 00:03:28,565
Now I'm going to Seattle to play music.

38
00:03:31,131 --> 00:03:33,122
[GUITAR PLAYING]

39
00:03:33,331 --> 00:03:35,322
[MATT SINGING]

40
00:03:44,251 --> 00:03:45,525
[POPS]

41
00:03:45,691 --> 00:03:48,251
Jesus Christ.

42
00:03:51,211 --> 00:03:54,169
I'm so sorry, man. I'm an idiot,
I wasn't paying attention.

43
00:03:54,331 --> 00:03:55,810
No. Forget about it, man.

44
00:03:55,971 --> 00:03:58,565
We're lucky this piece of shit
had a spare. Fuck.

45
00:03:58,731 --> 00:04:01,120
You ever changed a tire before, Martin?

46
00:04:01,291 --> 00:04:04,044
Didn't think so. Cool.

47
00:04:04,971 --> 00:04:07,360
Okay. What do we got here?

48
00:04:07,531 --> 00:04:10,887
Oh, yeah, I'll have us back on the road
in no time, no time at all.

49
00:04:11,051 --> 00:04:13,360
But this time, I'm driving. Cool?

50
00:04:16,331 --> 00:04:17,923
[GRUNTING]

51
00:04:18,251 --> 00:04:19,684
Fucker's on tight.

52
00:04:38,171 --> 00:04:43,040
First one's always the hardest. After that,
the rest of them come off pretty easy.

53
00:04:43,211 --> 00:04:44,690
[MATT WHISTLING]

54
00:04:46,611 --> 00:04:49,000
You and I are about
the same height, man.

55
00:04:49,691 --> 00:04:51,044
What?

56
00:04:52,851 --> 00:04:54,330
[TIRES SCREECHING]

57
00:05:40,811 --> 00:05:42,802
[MATT CHOKING]

58
00:06:08,731 --> 00:06:10,687
Shh.

59
00:06:11,371 --> 00:06:12,804
Be quiet.

60
00:06:31,531 --> 00:06:33,522
[SINGING MATT'S SONG]

61
00:09:52,971 --> 00:09:56,008
Officer. Officer, I need your help.

62
00:09:56,251 --> 00:09:59,049
I just saw my son on the ferry.

63
00:09:59,211 --> 00:10:00,803
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

64
00:10:01,251 --> 00:10:02,809
My son is dead.

65
00:10:02,971 --> 00:10:06,759
He died 19 years ago,
but this was my son.

66
00:10:06,931 --> 00:10:10,401
He walked straight in front of me.
We had eye contact.

67
00:10:10,611 --> 00:10:11,930
He recognized me.

68
00:10:12,211 --> 00:10:14,406
A mother's not wrong
about things like this.

69
00:10:16,011 --> 00:10:18,571
How can I explain
how dangerous he was, how...?

70
00:10:20,531 --> 00:10:22,647
No, not "was."

71
00:10:24,451 --> 00:10:25,770
Is.

72
00:10:26,691 --> 00:10:30,081
My son is a very dangerous man.

73
00:10:34,011 --> 00:10:35,922
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

74
00:10:37,611 --> 00:10:40,808
- What are you doing?
- Preparing a briefing for Agent Scott.

75
00:10:41,931 --> 00:10:43,523
Agent Scott?

76
00:10:43,691 --> 00:10:47,969
I don't understand why he needs someone
else. We've got everything under control.

77
00:10:48,131 --> 00:10:51,567
- We don't have anything, Joseph.
- Because we didn't have enough time.

78
00:10:51,731 --> 00:10:54,564
- We need a couple more days, that's it.
- She here yet?

79
00:10:54,891 --> 00:10:58,770
She was on the flight. They can't find
her. Gérard is checking baggage claim.

80
00:10:58,931 --> 00:11:02,367
- She's going to be advising, right?
- This isn't about territory, Paquette.

81
00:11:02,531 --> 00:11:05,045
PAQUETTE: There hasn't been
a murder like this in years.

82
00:11:05,211 --> 00:11:08,487
And the first thing you do is
bring in someone else. Come on.

83
00:11:08,651 --> 00:11:11,245
I have a strange feeling
about this murder.

84
00:11:11,691 --> 00:11:14,251
We need help. We have nothing.

85
00:11:14,731 --> 00:11:17,450
You call me as soon as she gets here.

86
00:11:54,571 --> 00:11:55,970
[CAR DOOR CLOSES]

87
00:12:05,611 --> 00:12:07,488
You got to be fucking kidding me.

88
00:12:07,651 --> 00:12:10,563
- Special Agent Scott?
- Yes.

89
00:12:11,691 --> 00:12:14,046
We were waiting for you at the station.

90
00:12:14,211 --> 00:12:17,089
PAQUETTE: That's a grave, you know.
- Yes, I know that.

91
00:12:19,531 --> 00:12:21,169
- Ah.
- Agent Scott.

92
00:12:21,331 --> 00:12:23,526
Monsieur Director, hello.

93
00:12:23,691 --> 00:12:26,205
I see you are already making
yourself comfortable.

94
00:12:26,371 --> 00:12:29,727
Joseph Paquette and Emile Duval.
They're leading the investigation.

95
00:12:29,891 --> 00:12:32,963
- Nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you. Thanks for inviting me.

96
00:12:33,131 --> 00:12:34,689
We didn't.

97
00:12:35,571 --> 00:12:39,280
We're pretty sure the victim was killed
somewhere else, then brought here.

98
00:12:40,331 --> 00:12:42,561
I think it was premeditated.

99
00:12:42,731 --> 00:12:44,722
PAQUETTE: What?
- I think it was premeditated.

100
00:12:44,891 --> 00:12:49,726
I think the killer chose this site,
specifically, and dug it in advance.

101
00:12:50,131 --> 00:12:53,328
I can show you... You can tell because...
See this? The corners?

102
00:12:53,491 --> 00:12:55,402
They're neat. They're symmetrical.

103
00:12:55,571 --> 00:12:57,687
The proportions are precise.

104
00:12:57,851 --> 00:13:00,160
They're exactly 5 foot, 11 inches.

105
00:13:00,331 --> 00:13:02,891
- Your victim 5-10?
- Yes, exactly.

106
00:13:04,131 --> 00:13:06,565
I think he's been watching him
for a few weeks...

107
00:13:06,731 --> 00:13:08,528
...studying his habits, his routine.

108
00:13:08,691 --> 00:13:11,603
And he knew he could rely
on digging the grave right here.

109
00:13:11,931 --> 00:13:15,367
And how did he know the victim
would be here when he wanted?

110
00:13:16,531 --> 00:13:18,806
That's a bicycle path, right?

111
00:13:18,971 --> 00:13:20,927
On the photos you sent...

112
00:13:21,091 --> 00:13:24,879
...the victim had these slight indentations
on his ankles.

113
00:13:25,171 --> 00:13:27,924
I'm guessing that's from bicycle clips.

114
00:13:28,331 --> 00:13:30,526
Also, there's a sexual element to all this.

115
00:13:30,691 --> 00:13:34,127
Strangling from behind, cutting off
the hands, smashing in the face.

116
00:13:34,291 --> 00:13:37,920
It's tactile. It's immediate.
It's what turns him on.

117
00:13:38,691 --> 00:13:40,329
And...

118
00:13:40,651 --> 00:13:42,448
...he wanted you to find the body.

119
00:13:42,851 --> 00:13:44,330
I mean...

120
00:13:44,491 --> 00:13:48,928
...why else bury it at a construction site,
unless you want it to be dug up, right?

121
00:14:33,931 --> 00:14:37,401
His eyes, we think they were removed,
or are they still in his skull?

122
00:14:37,571 --> 00:14:39,527
- We don't know.
- I assume you're doing...

123
00:14:39,691 --> 00:14:42,080
Skull reconstruction. Yes, of course.

124
00:14:42,251 --> 00:14:44,811
- It's being done right now.
- Okay.

125
00:14:45,091 --> 00:14:46,524
Are we done here?

126
00:14:46,691 --> 00:14:47,885
- Yeah.
- Okay.

127
00:14:48,251 --> 00:14:49,843
Good night.

128
00:14:50,251 --> 00:14:52,606
Don't worry about Paquette.
He's impulsive.

129
00:14:52,771 --> 00:14:54,523
He wants to rush into everything.

130
00:14:54,691 --> 00:14:56,010
I don't blame him.

131
00:14:56,451 --> 00:14:58,328
It's good to see you again, Illeana.

132
00:14:58,491 --> 00:15:00,686
Means a lot that you're up here.

133
00:15:00,851 --> 00:15:02,887
Lying in the grave.

134
00:15:03,371 --> 00:15:06,169
My investigators think
you are some kind of witch.

135
00:15:06,331 --> 00:15:07,810
Well, I've been called worse.

136
00:15:07,971 --> 00:15:10,439
- You know that.
- I know.

137
00:16:33,691 --> 00:16:35,170
[KNOCKS ON DOOR]

138
00:16:38,491 --> 00:16:41,563
Hi. I'm sorry for disturbing you.
A man was killed last night.

139
00:16:41,891 --> 00:16:45,406
It happened in a parking lot outside
a 24-hour health club around 9:00.

140
00:16:45,571 --> 00:16:47,402
- Same m.o.?
- Same everything.

141
00:16:47,571 --> 00:16:49,880
We found the garrotte there.
It looks homemade.

142
00:16:50,051 --> 00:16:52,121
The face was bashed
in with a loose stone.

143
00:16:52,291 --> 00:16:54,247
No time to get to the hands, though.

144
00:16:54,411 --> 00:16:57,289
- Why not?
- He was interrupted.

145
00:16:57,451 --> 00:17:01,126
The victim's name was Clive Morin,
and that's James Costa.

146
00:17:01,291 --> 00:17:02,963
He claims he saw what happened.

147
00:17:03,131 --> 00:17:05,042
COSTA:
He headed towards my car, and I hear...

148
00:17:05,211 --> 00:17:08,009
When our guys got there,
he was trying to revive the victim.

149
00:17:08,171 --> 00:17:09,763
PAQUETTE:
What about the blood on you?

150
00:17:09,931 --> 00:17:12,968
You try to help somebody
who's bleeding to death...

151
00:17:13,131 --> 00:17:15,440
ILLEANA: Is he checking out?
...you get blood on you.

152
00:17:15,771 --> 00:17:19,366
James McKeen Costa.
Born Nova Scotia, 1965.

153
00:17:19,531 --> 00:17:22,443
Everything looks pretty standard.

154
00:17:22,851 --> 00:17:25,968
We've got blood samples
and a DNA swab on the way to the lab.

155
00:17:26,131 --> 00:17:28,804
I turn, and I see...

156
00:17:29,531 --> 00:17:32,489
...a man standing over somebody else...

157
00:17:32,971 --> 00:17:34,563
...with...

158
00:17:35,491 --> 00:17:36,640
...a rock...

159
00:17:37,171 --> 00:17:38,889
...in his hand.

160
00:17:40,811 --> 00:17:42,244
And then...

161
00:17:42,411 --> 00:17:46,927
...he started beating
this guy's face in...

162
00:17:47,371 --> 00:17:50,568
- So I shouted...
- What did you shout?

163
00:17:52,651 --> 00:17:57,361
"Stop," you know. Something dumb
like that. I don't know. l...

164
00:17:57,531 --> 00:17:59,999
And then I ran towards them.

165
00:18:01,931 --> 00:18:05,719
And he looked up at me,
and he pointed a gun at me.

166
00:18:05,891 --> 00:18:09,008
And I...

167
00:18:11,011 --> 00:18:12,729
I don't know. I thought...

168
00:18:12,891 --> 00:18:15,200
I don't know what I thought.
Then he ran away.

169
00:18:15,371 --> 00:18:18,283
He's gone, and then I call the cops.

170
00:18:18,731 --> 00:18:23,680
And I tried to perform CPR on the
other guy until the paramedics came.

171
00:18:24,131 --> 00:18:26,247
Did you remove the garrotte?

172
00:18:26,411 --> 00:18:30,768
The...? Oh, the thing around his neck?
Yeah, I kind of had to.

173
00:18:31,291 --> 00:18:35,682
- Did you see where the attacker went?
- Yeah, he went far from me. Right?

174
00:18:35,851 --> 00:18:38,319
What kind of gun did he have?

175
00:18:39,211 --> 00:18:41,964
He had the kind that puts
really big holes in people.

176
00:18:45,131 --> 00:18:47,042
I saw this guy.

177
00:18:47,211 --> 00:18:50,203
All right? And I can draw a little bit,
all right? So...

178
00:18:50,371 --> 00:18:55,206
...maybe if you would give me a piece
of paper, I can sketch him for you.

179
00:18:55,651 --> 00:18:57,243
[DOOR OPENS]

180
00:19:01,571 --> 00:19:04,324
I don't know about this guy.
I can't read him.

181
00:19:04,491 --> 00:19:06,561
Something about his answers.

182
00:19:07,211 --> 00:19:08,644
You mind if I give it a try?

183
00:19:09,011 --> 00:19:10,922
No, please go ahead.

184
00:19:15,571 --> 00:19:17,050
Hi.

185
00:19:26,611 --> 00:19:28,090
You another cop?

186
00:19:28,251 --> 00:19:31,607
In a way, yes.
I'm Special Agent Illeana Scott.

187
00:19:32,091 --> 00:19:36,482
- Special agent?
- I'm FBI. I'm helping on the case.

188
00:19:42,571 --> 00:19:45,404
- Can I ask a few questions?
- You asking the same ones...

189
00:19:45,571 --> 00:19:48,165
...the other guy did?
- Yes, probably.

190
00:19:48,651 --> 00:19:52,087
- Do you mind if I have a cigarette?
- No, of course not.

191
00:20:11,491 --> 00:20:13,129
You nervous?

192
00:20:14,571 --> 00:20:17,131
Yes, I am.

193
00:20:17,291 --> 00:20:18,963
Extremely.

194
00:20:19,691 --> 00:20:21,647
Thanks for the pad of paper.

195
00:20:32,211 --> 00:20:34,202
So, what did he look like?

196
00:20:36,331 --> 00:20:38,720
He had extremely bright eyes.

197
00:20:39,211 --> 00:20:40,803
Burning, you know?

198
00:20:41,491 --> 00:20:43,083
Even in the dark.

199
00:20:43,251 --> 00:20:45,207
His hair...

200
00:20:45,971 --> 00:20:47,848
...could have been blond.

201
00:20:52,811 --> 00:20:54,642
He had a beard.

202
00:20:55,211 --> 00:20:58,169
He had, not five-o'clock shadow...

203
00:20:58,451 --> 00:20:59,884
...but something cultivated.

204
00:21:05,491 --> 00:21:07,686
Did he seem agitated or in control?

205
00:21:10,011 --> 00:21:11,364
COSTA:
Oh, Jesus.

206
00:21:11,531 --> 00:21:13,567
Is that what I think it is?

207
00:21:13,731 --> 00:21:15,050
Is that...? That's the...

208
00:21:15,211 --> 00:21:18,009
That was around his neck, right?
Am I right?

209
00:21:18,251 --> 00:21:19,684
- Am I right?
ILLEANA: Yes, yes.

210
00:21:19,851 --> 00:21:21,921
COSTA:
You did that on purpose?

211
00:21:22,091 --> 00:21:26,004
All right, I'm doing my best here, all right?
That man's face was half gone!

212
00:21:26,171 --> 00:21:28,401
I couldn't even...
It didn't even look human.

213
00:21:28,571 --> 00:21:32,086
I did everything I could
to try to help him, and he...

214
00:21:32,891 --> 00:21:36,042
He died, okay? He died. There was...

215
00:21:37,451 --> 00:21:42,241
Look, there was too much blood there.
I'd never seen so much blood in my life.

216
00:21:42,891 --> 00:21:46,008
And I kept trying,
even though I knew that it was too late.

217
00:21:46,891 --> 00:21:50,247
I saw the man who did this. Okay?

218
00:21:50,411 --> 00:21:54,245
I saw him, and I can show you
what he looks like.

219
00:21:55,491 --> 00:21:57,083
And then...

220
00:21:57,811 --> 00:21:59,244
...you can go catch him.

221
00:21:59,771 --> 00:22:00,965
Okay.

222
00:22:08,491 --> 00:22:09,810
What do you think?

223
00:22:09,971 --> 00:22:13,281
Yeah, pattern marks on Morin's neck
show the killer's left-handed.

224
00:22:13,451 --> 00:22:17,080
He sketches with his right,
tried to light a cigarette with his right.

225
00:22:17,251 --> 00:22:19,401
I think we need
a little more than that, no?

226
00:22:19,571 --> 00:22:22,039
I know. There's also
a file open on the table.

227
00:22:22,211 --> 00:22:24,566
It's your profile.
Evidence, notes, everything.

228
00:22:24,731 --> 00:22:28,007
If he were the killer, chances are
he'd be trying to take a look.

229
00:22:29,091 --> 00:22:31,889
Psychopaths actually have
very different brain patterns.

230
00:22:32,051 --> 00:22:37,887
You say words like "tree," "sofa,"
"house," "rape," "incest," "murder"...

231
00:22:38,051 --> 00:22:41,566
...a normal person's brain pattern
changes, their frontal lobe reacts.

232
00:22:41,731 --> 00:22:43,528
Psychopaths have no reaction.

233
00:22:44,091 --> 00:22:46,924
They feel the same about murder
as they do about dinner.

234
00:22:47,091 --> 00:22:48,809
They have no emotional connection.

235
00:22:49,731 --> 00:22:52,848
Anyway, my point is that
when he saw the garrotte...

236
00:22:53,011 --> 00:22:54,683
...he reacted...

237
00:22:54,851 --> 00:22:57,490
...with genuine shock and disgust.

238
00:23:02,131 --> 00:23:04,361
PAQUETTE:
A psychopath's brain?

239
00:23:06,011 --> 00:23:08,889
You learn a lot of that stuff
at the FBI, don't you?

240
00:23:09,051 --> 00:23:11,406
I mean, all those theories,
all those books.

241
00:23:11,571 --> 00:23:13,289
Yeah, that's right.

242
00:23:15,771 --> 00:23:18,410
I'm not sure what I see in you yet,
with your tricks.

243
00:23:20,411 --> 00:23:21,844
- I don't have any.
- Bullshit.

244
00:23:22,211 --> 00:23:24,247
You pulled a lot of them in that room.

245
00:23:24,491 --> 00:23:25,765
COSTA:
Agent Scott?

246
00:23:26,611 --> 00:23:29,603
- Could I talk to you for a second?
- Excuse me.

247
00:23:33,091 --> 00:23:37,562
My sisters get that look in their eye
when they're cornered and don't like it.

248
00:23:37,731 --> 00:23:40,086
- I'm sorry if I'm wrong, but...
- No.

249
00:23:40,251 --> 00:23:42,719
- Thank you.
- All right.

250
00:23:57,011 --> 00:24:00,606
PAQUETTE:
Henri Bisonnette, a freelance scuba diver.

251
00:24:00,771 --> 00:24:03,365
- Is that our construction site body?
PAQUETTE: Yes.

252
00:24:03,531 --> 00:24:05,806
His sister identified him.

253
00:24:06,931 --> 00:24:10,048
Bisonnette used to work for him
on and off for a few years.

254
00:24:10,211 --> 00:24:13,760
Also, his sister said he disappeared
just about a couple of weeks ago.

255
00:24:14,051 --> 00:24:17,088
But his credit cards have been
in use all this time.

256
00:24:23,291 --> 00:24:25,725
What kind of a man was he?
What do we know?

257
00:24:26,131 --> 00:24:28,281
He lived in a small apartment...

258
00:24:28,651 --> 00:24:31,211
...picked up odd computer jobs...

259
00:24:31,691 --> 00:24:33,568
...didn't have a lot of friends.

260
00:24:34,371 --> 00:24:36,202
You ever do that? Go diving?

261
00:24:36,931 --> 00:24:39,843
My ex-wife made us take
one of those Club Med holidays.

262
00:24:40,011 --> 00:24:43,367
She wasn't down 20 feet
before she freaked out. Couldn't take it.

263
00:24:52,611 --> 00:24:54,203
PAQUETTE:
That's a good one.

264
00:24:57,851 --> 00:24:59,762
Have you ever gone diving,
Agent Scott?

265
00:25:03,211 --> 00:25:04,690
No, I've never tried it.

266
00:25:04,851 --> 00:25:06,079
[PHONE RINGING]

267
00:25:06,251 --> 00:25:07,525
DUVAL: It's very serene.
- Oui?

268
00:25:07,691 --> 00:25:10,967
The fish swim all around you.
They don't even mind you're there.

269
00:25:11,251 --> 00:25:13,526
You'd like it, it's quiet.

270
00:25:13,691 --> 00:25:14,965
[PHONE DROPS]

271
00:25:15,131 --> 00:25:17,122
- I've got a hit on that sketch.
- Where?

272
00:25:17,291 --> 00:25:19,327
Some residential hotel near the river.

273
00:25:19,851 --> 00:25:22,319
- What are you doing?
- Shouldn't we be going?

274
00:25:23,491 --> 00:25:25,721
We're still eating our breakfast.

275
00:25:40,931 --> 00:25:42,808
- Follow me.
- Thank you.

276
00:25:43,131 --> 00:25:46,362
So he paid me cash three months
in advance, and I never see him.

277
00:25:46,531 --> 00:25:48,044
Did you see him here?

278
00:25:48,651 --> 00:25:50,482
MAN:
Yeah, that's him.

279
00:25:50,651 --> 00:25:54,769
But before you guys bust him, he kind of
owes me $90 on the phone bill.

280
00:25:54,931 --> 00:25:57,240
Maybe you guys can take care of that.

281
00:25:58,091 --> 00:26:01,527
You know what?
We need that phone bill.

282
00:26:02,731 --> 00:26:05,928
- All right. You guys gonna pay it?
PAQUETTE: We'll see.

283
00:26:12,531 --> 00:26:13,964
[BANGS]

284
00:26:19,571 --> 00:26:21,562
[WATER RUNNING]

285
00:26:41,971 --> 00:26:43,290
[SNIFFS]

286
00:28:54,651 --> 00:28:56,562
DUVAL:
Everything's clear.

287
00:29:28,051 --> 00:29:30,121
- Oh, shit.
- What?

288
00:29:30,811 --> 00:29:31,846
Ah!

289
00:29:42,371 --> 00:29:47,047
The ring from the finger was engraved
with the name Clark William Edwards.

290
00:29:47,211 --> 00:29:49,088
It's from Vancouver Secondary School.

291
00:29:49,251 --> 00:29:53,290
Thirty-four years old.
Works part-time on an Alaskan cruise line.

292
00:29:53,451 --> 00:29:56,329
His credit card was used yesterday
in Montreal.

293
00:29:56,491 --> 00:29:58,721
- He had not been reported missing.
- Good.

294
00:29:58,891 --> 00:30:00,802
- Let's keep it that way.
- Why?

295
00:30:00,971 --> 00:30:03,041
Let's not reward the killer
with coverage.

296
00:30:03,211 --> 00:30:05,122
He likes attention. He'll be pissed.

297
00:30:05,291 --> 00:30:07,566
If he's pissed off, he'll make a mistake.

298
00:30:07,771 --> 00:30:10,001
We should put a marker
on Edwards' credit card...

299
00:30:10,171 --> 00:30:12,526
...and order surveillance of this place.

300
00:30:12,931 --> 00:30:15,320
- So we're getting close.
- One more thing.

301
00:30:15,491 --> 00:30:17,686
The lab results on Costa's DNA came in.

302
00:30:17,851 --> 00:30:20,809
- He's clean.
- Good.

303
00:30:21,011 --> 00:30:22,808
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

304
00:30:45,051 --> 00:30:46,848
[LAUGHING]

305
00:30:47,731 --> 00:30:49,369
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

306
00:31:18,371 --> 00:31:19,770
COSTA:
Man...

307
00:31:20,251 --> 00:31:22,685
You got those coffees and a sandwich?

308
00:31:28,771 --> 00:31:31,160
So this isn't a coincidence, right?

309
00:31:31,331 --> 00:31:32,684
ILLEANA:
No.

310
00:31:33,211 --> 00:31:36,920
The two cops outside the gallery?
That's not a coincidence either, right?

311
00:31:37,091 --> 00:31:39,047
Does that bother you?

312
00:31:39,691 --> 00:31:43,479
I've been looking over my shoulder
since this whole thing happened, so no.

313
00:31:44,331 --> 00:31:47,721
- I'm glad for the company.
- How are you doing?

314
00:31:49,571 --> 00:31:51,448
I can't sleep.

315
00:31:51,611 --> 00:31:53,203
But that's all right.

316
00:31:53,371 --> 00:31:56,090
I have a giant show on Friday,
bunch of new paintings.

317
00:31:56,251 --> 00:31:58,287
If I don't sell them,
I'm gonna go broke.

318
00:31:58,451 --> 00:32:01,124
So I'm throwing myself into my work.
Kind of like you.

319
00:32:04,931 --> 00:32:06,523
- Here you go.
- Keep it. Thanks.

320
00:32:06,691 --> 00:32:10,081
Did you get any responses
to the sketch?

321
00:32:11,491 --> 00:32:13,083
Maybe.

322
00:32:16,611 --> 00:32:18,124
You're being vague.

323
00:32:27,491 --> 00:32:30,642
That night, do you remember
Clive Morin fighting back?

324
00:32:32,611 --> 00:32:34,408
Um, uh...

325
00:32:35,931 --> 00:32:37,250
I mean, you know...

326
00:32:37,411 --> 00:32:42,485
...it took me a couple seconds to see,
even register, what was going on.

327
00:32:42,651 --> 00:32:44,926
I heard these sounds,
I saw him with the rock.

328
00:32:45,091 --> 00:32:48,481
By the time I saw Clive Morin...

329
00:32:48,651 --> 00:32:52,803
...you know, he wasn't doing anything.

330
00:32:56,131 --> 00:32:57,405
How do you know CPR?

331
00:32:58,651 --> 00:32:59,800
I don't.

332
00:32:59,971 --> 00:33:02,087
I mean, l...

333
00:33:02,251 --> 00:33:04,924
I tried to do CPR on him...

334
00:33:05,091 --> 00:33:07,730
...but I just did what I could, you know?

335
00:33:07,891 --> 00:33:10,530
I imitated what I've seen on TV.

336
00:33:12,651 --> 00:33:15,245
You looking at my fingers?
You looking at this?

337
00:33:15,411 --> 00:33:17,641
- Yes.
- You're, like, looking at everything.

338
00:33:17,811 --> 00:33:22,009
No, this is... This is... l...
I make my own frames.

339
00:33:22,171 --> 00:33:24,560
You know, and I...

340
00:33:24,731 --> 00:33:28,121
The closer we get to the show,
the worse my accuracy is.

341
00:33:32,091 --> 00:33:36,209
I'd like to buy you a cup of coffee,
but it looks like you have a problem.

342
00:33:37,011 --> 00:33:40,083
Well, the first step is admitting to it.

343
00:33:41,091 --> 00:33:45,243
Is that a sense of humor?
Is that what that is? It is.

344
00:33:45,411 --> 00:33:47,845
All that and... What's this?

345
00:33:52,971 --> 00:33:56,725
My cell phone number,
in case you remember anything else.

346
00:33:57,371 --> 00:33:59,601
Anything that might be helpful.

347
00:33:59,771 --> 00:34:01,568
Okay.

348
00:34:02,931 --> 00:34:04,842
All right. Well, thanks.

349
00:34:05,651 --> 00:34:08,211
Okay, I'll...

350
00:34:08,371 --> 00:34:10,931
Maybe you want to come
to the show on Friday night.

351
00:34:11,091 --> 00:34:14,800
You know, I think you'd like it.
Lots of strange, disturbing pieces.

352
00:34:16,251 --> 00:34:17,969
All right.

353
00:34:24,931 --> 00:34:27,968
Whoever was in that hotel room
called this number 20 times.

354
00:34:28,531 --> 00:34:30,283
"Rebecca Asher."

355
00:34:30,451 --> 00:34:32,282
DUVAL:
She claimed to have seen her son...

356
00:34:32,451 --> 00:34:34,646
...at the Quebec ferry terminal
three weeks ago.

357
00:34:34,811 --> 00:34:40,010
- And what do we know about her?
- In her late 60s, no husband, lives alone.

358
00:34:45,371 --> 00:34:48,886
I'm gonna handle this one
on my own, I think. Okay?

359
00:35:01,291 --> 00:35:02,690
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

360
00:35:04,971 --> 00:35:07,360
ILLEANA: I know you've seen
this picture on the news...

361
00:35:07,531 --> 00:35:10,284
...but if you could take
a closer look at it, please?

362
00:35:12,291 --> 00:35:14,009
Of course.

363
00:35:18,411 --> 00:35:20,208
ILLEANA:
Could that be your son?

364
00:35:21,051 --> 00:35:22,564
It could be.

365
00:35:24,771 --> 00:35:26,170
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

366
00:35:30,571 --> 00:35:32,368
I recognized him on the ferry.

367
00:35:32,731 --> 00:35:35,848
He had a full beard,
hat low on his forehead.

368
00:35:36,691 --> 00:35:38,807
But his eyes...

369
00:35:38,971 --> 00:35:40,848
...they were unmistakable.

370
00:35:43,091 --> 00:35:46,845
And he was pulling on his ear.

371
00:35:47,011 --> 00:35:49,684
It's an old nervous tic from childhood.

372
00:35:50,531 --> 00:35:53,443
I could never get him to break it.

373
00:35:53,611 --> 00:35:57,445
Were you ever actually asked
to identify a body years ago?

374
00:35:59,891 --> 00:36:02,166
They showed me some remains...

375
00:36:02,331 --> 00:36:05,129
...that had been hit by a truck.

376
00:36:07,171 --> 00:36:11,164
I can't say that I was
in any way prepared for it.

377
00:36:11,331 --> 00:36:13,162
No, of course not.

378
00:36:13,331 --> 00:36:15,128
I'm sorry.

379
00:36:20,451 --> 00:36:22,760
- May I?
- Please.

380
00:36:30,651 --> 00:36:32,130
Martin.

381
00:36:32,291 --> 00:36:35,169
No. No, that is Reese.

382
00:36:35,331 --> 00:36:38,289
- That's Martin's older brother.
- Oh.

383
00:36:38,451 --> 00:36:41,204
By older, I mean three minutes.

384
00:36:41,371 --> 00:36:43,965
- Twins?
- Identical.

385
00:36:44,491 --> 00:36:49,724
Has Reese been receiving
any strange phone calls, or...?

386
00:36:51,251 --> 00:36:53,526
Of course you couldn't know.

387
00:36:53,851 --> 00:36:55,125
Reese passed away.

388
00:36:55,971 --> 00:36:58,326
Oh, I'm sorry.

389
00:36:58,971 --> 00:37:00,848
They were 14.

390
00:37:01,011 --> 00:37:03,571
They took a raft out on the Saint Michel.

391
00:37:04,091 --> 00:37:06,810
There had been a very big
snow melt-off that year...

392
00:37:06,971 --> 00:37:09,121
...and Martin fell overboard.

393
00:37:09,291 --> 00:37:11,680
Reese jumped in to save him.

394
00:37:12,691 --> 00:37:15,125
Only Martin reached the shore.

395
00:37:16,491 --> 00:37:19,688
- That must have been devastating for you.
- It was.

396
00:37:22,451 --> 00:37:24,442
Well, it was for Martin too.

397
00:37:25,691 --> 00:37:27,602
You know, Reese...

398
00:37:30,331 --> 00:37:32,162
He was just charismatic...

399
00:37:32,491 --> 00:37:34,482
...outgoing.

400
00:37:34,651 --> 00:37:38,087
After he died,
Martin just took a strange turn.

401
00:37:38,251 --> 00:37:40,082
He became violent.

402
00:37:41,051 --> 00:37:45,203
And when he was 16, he stole
most of my jewelry and ran away.

403
00:37:46,011 --> 00:37:49,162
The police from St. Jovite
called me just a few days later...

404
00:37:50,011 --> 00:37:51,842
...telling me about the accident.

405
00:37:54,051 --> 00:37:55,450
That's a great one.

406
00:37:55,611 --> 00:37:57,010
MRS. ASHER:
Oh, yes.

407
00:37:57,171 --> 00:38:00,163
Summer vacation, Fort Rupert.

408
00:38:00,331 --> 00:38:01,525
ILLEANA:
And this?

409
00:38:01,691 --> 00:38:04,763
MRS. ASHER:
Oh, that was our first symphony.

410
00:38:05,051 --> 00:38:07,645
- The Magic Flute.
- Of course.

411
00:38:07,811 --> 00:38:09,005
He's cute.

412
00:38:09,171 --> 00:38:10,968
He was.

413
00:38:12,731 --> 00:38:14,687
He was cute.

414
00:38:19,611 --> 00:38:21,681
Now, that's Martin.

415
00:38:21,851 --> 00:38:24,490
He always had to wear those big glasses.

416
00:38:24,651 --> 00:38:27,848
Half the time, I couldn't tell them apart
unless he had those on.

417
00:38:30,011 --> 00:38:31,763
Here, I'll just take...

418
00:38:32,091 --> 00:38:34,207
...that thing for you.

419
00:38:36,051 --> 00:38:39,680
- Oh, I forgot my purse. I'll just be...
- I'll get it.

420
00:38:57,211 --> 00:38:58,769
Here you are.

421
00:38:58,931 --> 00:39:01,889
Thanks. I appreciate your time.
You've been very helpful.

422
00:39:02,811 --> 00:39:05,200
You will call me
when you find him, won't you?

423
00:39:05,371 --> 00:39:06,850
Yes, of course.

424
00:39:07,651 --> 00:39:09,403
Good.

425
00:39:16,531 --> 00:39:17,850
DUVAL:
So?

426
00:39:18,011 --> 00:39:20,241
How long does it take here
to dig up a body?

427
00:39:20,411 --> 00:39:22,208
[WOOD CREAKING]

428
00:39:34,971 --> 00:39:39,408
According to his mother, Martin Asher
had only broken one bone in his life:

429
00:39:39,571 --> 00:39:43,200
The left radius,
falling off a chair or something.

430
00:39:43,371 --> 00:39:46,408
This kid broke a lot of bones.

431
00:39:46,571 --> 00:39:49,643
Mostly in his face, hands and torso.

432
00:39:51,691 --> 00:39:55,240
But as you can see,
the left radius is intact.

433
00:39:55,731 --> 00:39:58,040
This isn't the body of Martin Asher.

434
00:39:59,731 --> 00:40:03,007
Okay. We better
get Mrs. Asher someplace safe.

435
00:40:05,051 --> 00:40:07,201
DESK CLERK:
Here, Mrs. Asher, 601.

436
00:40:07,371 --> 00:40:09,601
No, no. I'm afraid that room
is unacceptable.

437
00:40:09,771 --> 00:40:11,443
It's too near the elevator.

438
00:40:11,611 --> 00:40:16,401
- How'd she talk you into putting her here?
- Mrs. Asher has a way with words.

439
00:40:17,531 --> 00:40:18,759
She's hiding something.

440
00:40:18,931 --> 00:40:21,604
There's a door in the house
hidden by a bookcase.

441
00:40:21,771 --> 00:40:24,205
Her house is under
the department's protection...

442
00:40:24,371 --> 00:40:26,327
...but we can't just go and search it.

443
00:40:26,491 --> 00:40:31,485
Well, what about a headstrong FBI agent
who's just not familiar with the rules?

444
00:40:31,651 --> 00:40:33,323
Now, that's a different story.

445
00:40:48,291 --> 00:40:49,565
[CLICKS]

446
00:40:56,091 --> 00:40:57,922
[WOOD SCRAPES]

447
00:41:05,571 --> 00:41:07,209
[LIGHT SWITCH CLICKS]

448
00:43:25,651 --> 00:43:26,925
ILLEANA:
There you are.

449
00:43:31,131 --> 00:43:32,405
[SCREAMS]

450
00:44:15,931 --> 00:44:17,330
[PHONE RINGING]

451
00:44:20,451 --> 00:44:22,009
- Scott.
DUVAL: Illeana.

452
00:44:22,171 --> 00:44:26,005
The crime scene investigators think he
came in through a second story window.

453
00:44:26,171 --> 00:44:28,241
Mrs. Asher claims no one else has a key.

454
00:44:28,411 --> 00:44:31,403
And so far, the fingerprints
haven 't turned up anything.

455
00:44:31,571 --> 00:44:35,803
- How are you feeling? You okay?
- I'm fine.

456
00:44:35,971 --> 00:44:38,360
- Are you sure?
- I'm fine.

457
00:44:38,531 --> 00:44:41,648
Illeana, Leclair knows
you were at the house.

458
00:44:41,811 --> 00:44:44,723
I don 't think he connected you
with anything else...

459
00:44:44,891 --> 00:44:48,440
Could...? Would you come to the office
about an hour early tomorrow?

460
00:44:48,611 --> 00:44:49,885
Sure.

461
00:44:50,051 --> 00:44:51,803
- I'll see you there.
- Bye.

462
00:44:56,491 --> 00:44:57,844
ILLEANA:
Taking lives.

463
00:44:58,011 --> 00:45:01,447
That's what Martin Asher's
been doing for almost 20 years.

464
00:45:01,611 --> 00:45:03,010
His first victim, John Doe.

465
00:45:03,171 --> 00:45:05,924
He was clumsier then.
He covered with a car accident...

466
00:45:06,091 --> 00:45:09,208
...to fake his own death,
and then he took the boy's identity.

467
00:45:09,371 --> 00:45:12,090
There's a gap between
John Doe and Henri Bisonnette...

468
00:45:12,251 --> 00:45:14,526
...but that doesn't mean
Asher was dormant.

469
00:45:14,691 --> 00:45:18,604
Yes, ViCLAS gave us 19 unsolved murders
throughout eastern Canada.

470
00:45:18,771 --> 00:45:20,523
At least 11 match the m.o.

471
00:45:20,691 --> 00:45:24,684
All who either lived solitary lives
or simply would not be missed right away.

472
00:45:24,851 --> 00:45:28,207
Henri Bisonnette. Asher kills him,
takes his life, his apartment...

473
00:45:28,371 --> 00:45:30,805
...uses his credit cards.
He even pays his taxes.

474
00:45:30,971 --> 00:45:34,805
Nothing extravagant.
He's just living Bisonnette's life.

475
00:45:34,971 --> 00:45:39,249
Then he drops him for Clark William
Edwards, and as Edwards he stalks Morin.

476
00:45:39,411 --> 00:45:42,847
All of these men have something in
common, something that he desires.

477
00:45:43,011 --> 00:45:46,162
Simply, a life different from his own.

478
00:45:46,491 --> 00:45:48,129
I met his mother.

479
00:45:48,291 --> 00:45:50,805
Asher had a twin brother
who she clearly favored.

480
00:45:51,011 --> 00:45:56,210
So this guy can't stand to be
who he actually is for even a moment.

481
00:45:56,571 --> 00:45:58,323
So...

482
00:45:58,491 --> 00:46:00,209
...he overlaps bodies.

483
00:46:00,931 --> 00:46:02,364
He's like a hermit crab.

484
00:46:02,531 --> 00:46:05,967
He outgrows one shell,
and he starts looking for a new one.

485
00:46:07,051 --> 00:46:09,246
So, guys, the message is clear, right?

486
00:46:09,411 --> 00:46:12,608
He's outside looking for his next victim.

487
00:46:13,691 --> 00:46:15,568
Thank you, Illeana.

488
00:46:16,451 --> 00:46:17,964
Okay.

489
00:46:18,451 --> 00:46:20,760
Someone just broke
into James Costa's gallery.

490
00:46:21,091 --> 00:46:24,925
All that's missing is my organizer
and a business checkbook? Nothing else?

491
00:46:25,091 --> 00:46:27,207
PAQUETTE: The alarm system was cut.
- Yeah, right.

492
00:46:27,371 --> 00:46:30,363
So this doesn't feel
like a normal break-in?

493
00:46:30,931 --> 00:46:32,922
DUVAL:
What happened tonight, Mr. Costa?

494
00:46:33,091 --> 00:46:36,447
Right, listen,
I do all my calls to Europe at night.

495
00:46:36,611 --> 00:46:38,249
All my shipping stuff at night.

496
00:46:38,411 --> 00:46:41,528
I want a cup of coffee,
I go to the diner across the street.

497
00:46:41,691 --> 00:46:45,161
I come back in, the door's busted open,
and my desk is all messed up.

498
00:46:45,531 --> 00:46:46,964
You think it's him, right?

499
00:46:47,131 --> 00:46:52,046
DUVAL: We'll assign more officers to your
apartment until we're sure it's nothing.

500
00:46:52,211 --> 00:46:56,648
COSTA: That answers my question.
- Clark William Edwards.

501
00:46:57,131 --> 00:47:00,680
You're meeting with someone named
Clark William Edwards tomorrow night?

502
00:47:00,851 --> 00:47:04,639
- Is that right?
- Yeah. He's a potential buyer.

503
00:47:06,371 --> 00:47:08,327
His rep called me up yesterday.

504
00:47:10,251 --> 00:47:11,843
Could be a really big client.

505
00:47:14,731 --> 00:47:15,925
You're kidding me.

506
00:47:17,171 --> 00:47:19,844
We'll have undercover officers
watching all the time.

507
00:47:20,011 --> 00:47:21,490
The best surveillance team.

508
00:47:21,651 --> 00:47:25,246
We're still talking about the same guy
who smashes in people's faces...

509
00:47:25,411 --> 00:47:27,049
...and cuts off their hands?

510
00:47:28,211 --> 00:47:31,089
PAQUETTE: He won't come
within 50 yards of you, okay?

511
00:47:31,251 --> 00:47:34,209
DUVAL: It would be a great service
to the city of Montreal.

512
00:47:35,811 --> 00:47:40,248
It is dangerous, but it is probably
our best shot at catching this guy.

513
00:47:44,211 --> 00:47:45,610
All right?

514
00:47:47,491 --> 00:47:50,244
All right. All right.

515
00:47:50,411 --> 00:47:53,960
But only in service
to the great city of Montreal.

516
00:47:57,451 --> 00:47:59,601
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

517
00:47:59,851 --> 00:48:01,569
Is he gonna drive me home?

518
00:48:01,731 --> 00:48:04,245
Could Agent Scott drive me home?

519
00:48:08,331 --> 00:48:11,084
I should have stayed
in Winnipeg, you know?

520
00:48:11,251 --> 00:48:15,290
I had a nice gallery, three paintings
on the wall, nobody ever came in.

521
00:48:15,451 --> 00:48:19,763
If you stayed there, we wouldn't have had
a witness who could draw the killer.

522
00:48:19,931 --> 00:48:22,001
And that's made a big difference.

523
00:48:24,811 --> 00:48:27,405
- That's a generous way of looking at it.
- Left here?

524
00:48:27,571 --> 00:48:31,120
No, just keep going straight,
past Chevalier.

525
00:48:40,011 --> 00:48:42,366
Can I...?

526
00:48:42,531 --> 00:48:44,442
Can I ask you a question?

527
00:48:45,091 --> 00:48:46,240
Yes.

528
00:48:46,411 --> 00:48:48,163
How do you do it?

529
00:48:48,331 --> 00:48:51,846
How do you live your life
surrounded by all this...

530
00:48:52,011 --> 00:48:55,526
...ugliness? You know,
I mean, murderers...

531
00:48:55,691 --> 00:48:57,921
...and victims and these pictures,
you know?

532
00:48:59,131 --> 00:49:03,044
What I'm going through, just a little bit,
is what you live every day, right?

533
00:49:03,211 --> 00:49:06,009
- This is my job.
- There are different jobs.

534
00:49:06,171 --> 00:49:09,880
- There are better jobs.
- Not for me. No there isn't. 219?

535
00:49:10,531 --> 00:49:12,761
219? Yeah, yeah, right up here.

536
00:49:25,171 --> 00:49:29,847
What does Mr. Agent Scott
think about all this?

537
00:49:30,371 --> 00:49:32,123
I'm not married.

538
00:49:32,291 --> 00:49:34,805
I just... I just wear that.

539
00:49:39,611 --> 00:49:41,090
[KNOCKS IN WINDOW]

540
00:49:41,251 --> 00:49:44,561
- Walk you to the door, Mr. Costa?
- Yeah, great. I'll...

541
00:49:46,091 --> 00:49:48,366
So listen, tomorrow...

542
00:49:49,331 --> 00:49:51,208
It's gonna be okay.

543
00:49:51,371 --> 00:49:53,168
Try to get some sleep.

544
00:49:53,811 --> 00:49:56,530
Then I'll look forward
to seeing you tomorrow, okay?

545
00:50:10,931 --> 00:50:13,843
Is there some kind of signal
I should give if I need help?

546
00:50:14,011 --> 00:50:16,127
- You know, like...
PAQUETTE: No need.

547
00:50:16,291 --> 00:50:17,610
All eyes will be on you.

548
00:50:17,771 --> 00:50:20,683
DUVAL: We've got five men on the inside
and a dozen outside.

549
00:50:20,851 --> 00:50:25,083
So don't worry. When he shows up,
we'll be right on top of him.

550
00:50:25,251 --> 00:50:27,082
Well, that's a comfort.

551
00:50:33,771 --> 00:50:35,841
[CROWD CHATTERING]

552
00:51:06,531 --> 00:51:07,805
BARTENDER:
Everything okay?

553
00:51:07,971 --> 00:51:10,485
- What?
- Would you like another?

554
00:51:10,651 --> 00:51:13,643
- Refill?
- Oh, yeah. Yeah.

555
00:51:13,811 --> 00:51:16,450
BARTENDER: Scotch, right?
- Yeah.

556
00:51:29,811 --> 00:51:31,164
He's late.

557
00:51:31,331 --> 00:51:32,525
Yes, he is.

558
00:52:15,291 --> 00:52:18,522
COSTA: I just got a note. It says,
"Meet me in the men's room."

559
00:52:20,131 --> 00:52:23,567
MAN: We've lost Costa 's mike.
I'm working on it.

560
00:52:23,731 --> 00:52:27,007
There's too much interference
in the club.

561
00:52:30,091 --> 00:52:32,525
COSTA:
l... I'll go, all right?

562
00:52:52,411 --> 00:52:54,686
Is anybody fucking there?

563
00:52:58,291 --> 00:53:00,247
Hello?

564
00:53:04,651 --> 00:53:06,881
I'm going to the restroom.

565
00:53:40,171 --> 00:53:42,401
Meet me outside.

566
00:53:44,971 --> 00:53:46,120
What's going on?

567
00:53:46,291 --> 00:53:49,966
DUVAL: We thought it best to cut it off.
- I was sitting in there for two hours.

568
00:53:50,131 --> 00:53:52,850
- He must've made us.
- "Made us"? What does that mean?

569
00:53:53,011 --> 00:53:54,808
He saw you?
He knows what's happening?

570
00:53:54,971 --> 00:53:56,689
He knows I'm cooperating with police?

571
00:53:56,851 --> 00:54:00,526
PAQUETTE: Take it easy, okay?
- Take it easy? Have you ever been fishing?

572
00:54:00,691 --> 00:54:02,727
The bait always dies.

573
00:54:06,809 --> 00:54:08,401
Oh, boy.

574
00:54:12,329 --> 00:54:17,084
This ought to provide you
with some juicy profiling material.

575
00:54:17,249 --> 00:54:19,319
Single art dealer...

576
00:54:19,489 --> 00:54:24,085
...living in constant state
of organized chaos.

577
00:54:24,249 --> 00:54:28,242
Purchases firearm, even though
he doesn't know how to use one...

578
00:54:28,409 --> 00:54:31,765
...for a false sense of security.

579
00:54:34,529 --> 00:54:37,999
- You... You can come in, you know.
- No, it's all right. Thank you.

580
00:54:39,129 --> 00:54:41,040
You two, back door.

581
00:54:42,449 --> 00:54:44,758
You'll be safe.
You have two guys in back...

582
00:54:44,929 --> 00:54:46,965
...and two in the hallway. Okay?
- Great.

583
00:54:52,609 --> 00:54:54,839
Just going to check the street
one more time.

584
00:54:55,009 --> 00:54:58,285
If you need anything, you know how
to get me, Duval or Paquette?

585
00:54:58,449 --> 00:55:00,917
- Yeah. Back there at the bar...
- It's okay.

586
00:55:01,089 --> 00:55:03,967
No, I really wish
I didn't freak out like that.

587
00:55:05,009 --> 00:55:07,239
I wasn't helping anybody.

588
00:55:07,729 --> 00:55:09,082
You've been great.

589
00:55:09,249 --> 00:55:11,638
You're making me sound nicer than I am.

590
00:55:12,009 --> 00:55:14,762
- You are nice.
- No. That's...

591
00:55:14,929 --> 00:55:16,521
That's the kiss of death.

592
00:55:16,689 --> 00:55:18,042
What do you mean?

593
00:55:19,329 --> 00:55:21,479
Us nice guys never get the girl.

594
00:55:29,489 --> 00:55:31,286
I should go.

595
00:55:31,449 --> 00:55:33,007
You know how to find us.

596
00:55:45,089 --> 00:55:46,841
ILLEANA:
So I'm leaving.

597
00:55:47,649 --> 00:55:48,968
What do you mean?

598
00:55:49,129 --> 00:55:50,278
My job is done here.

599
00:55:50,449 --> 00:55:53,566
You have a profile and a witness.
You don't need me anymore.

600
00:55:53,729 --> 00:55:55,924
Illeana...

601
00:55:56,089 --> 00:55:58,523
...we need someone who can get
into Asher's head.

602
00:55:58,689 --> 00:56:01,999
- You have that, and you have a suspect.
- That might not be enough.

603
00:56:04,169 --> 00:56:05,841
What's really going on here?

604
00:56:06,009 --> 00:56:07,681
Nothing.

605
00:56:08,169 --> 00:56:10,558
Please. What is it?

606
00:56:12,169 --> 00:56:15,206
I might be having a reaction
to the witness.

607
00:56:15,369 --> 00:56:17,246
A reaction?

608
00:56:18,009 --> 00:56:19,761
Favorable.

609
00:56:20,369 --> 00:56:22,678
One that could cloud my judgment.

610
00:56:22,849 --> 00:56:24,521
I see.

611
00:56:27,129 --> 00:56:28,926
Illeana...

612
00:56:29,089 --> 00:56:32,001
...how long did we know each other
when I was at Quantico?

613
00:56:32,169 --> 00:56:34,046
- Six months.
- How many times...

614
00:56:34,209 --> 00:56:37,121
...were you asked for a drink?
- I don't know.

615
00:56:37,289 --> 00:56:39,200
How many times
did you turn them down?

616
00:56:39,369 --> 00:56:40,643
- Every time.
- Well...

617
00:56:40,809 --> 00:56:43,482
...I think it takes a lot
to cloud your judgment.

618
00:56:43,649 --> 00:56:48,006
Listen, I have to catch this guy.
I know you. You have to catch him too.

619
00:56:48,529 --> 00:56:50,326
I really need you.

620
00:56:51,729 --> 00:56:53,481
Please.

621
00:56:54,129 --> 00:56:56,882
[PARTIERS CHEERING]

622
00:57:13,929 --> 00:57:15,203
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

623
00:57:17,249 --> 00:57:19,399
DUVAL:
At least the food is good.

624
00:57:20,169 --> 00:57:23,161
PAQUETTE:
Yeah, because the art is shit.

625
00:57:24,649 --> 00:57:26,958
Try not to look so much like cops.

626
00:57:38,849 --> 00:57:42,046
I almost didn't recognize you
without a picture of a dead body.

627
00:57:42,209 --> 00:57:45,087
- That's nice.
- It sounded better in my head.

628
00:57:45,249 --> 00:57:46,841
- Have a drink.
- No, thank you.

629
00:57:47,009 --> 00:57:49,000
I mean, it's just water.

630
00:57:49,369 --> 00:57:51,280
- All right?
- Thank you.

631
00:57:52,809 --> 00:57:56,085
- Excuse me.
- This one is my favorite.

632
00:57:56,249 --> 00:57:59,161
You know, it just...
I don't know why. The sky...

633
00:57:59,329 --> 00:58:02,321
The sky in it reminds me
of growing up in Nova Scotia.

634
00:58:04,049 --> 00:58:05,721
Where'd you grow up?

635
00:58:05,889 --> 00:58:10,724
- Just outside Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
- Oh, yeah? You a country girl?

636
00:58:10,889 --> 00:58:13,323
- I'll let you get back to work.
- Thank you.

637
00:58:23,489 --> 00:58:24,888
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

638
00:58:40,089 --> 00:58:41,442
It's him.

639
00:58:42,329 --> 00:58:43,921
PAQUETTE:
Freeze!

640
00:58:46,369 --> 00:58:48,166
[CROWD SCREAMING]

641
00:59:25,289 --> 00:59:27,120
[CROWD YELLING IN FRENCH]

642
00:59:42,849 --> 00:59:44,646
[FIREWORKS EXPLODING]

643
00:59:46,649 --> 00:59:48,640
[BAND PLAYING]

644
01:00:16,289 --> 01:00:18,086
So now he's running loose again.

645
01:00:18,249 --> 01:00:20,922
We lost him in the crowd.
It was a fucking mob scene.

646
01:00:21,089 --> 01:00:23,649
LECLAIR:
"Fucking mob scene." And Costa?

647
01:00:23,809 --> 01:00:26,084
Shaken up, but he wasn't hurt.

648
01:00:26,849 --> 01:00:28,726
LECLAIR:
What do you think his next move is?

649
01:00:28,889 --> 01:00:32,040
I think he sees James Costa
as unfinished business.

650
01:00:32,209 --> 01:00:36,282
We've got Costa on a flight
to Toronto tomorrow morning at 8:30.

651
01:00:37,089 --> 01:00:40,206
Then I want one of you to take him
personally to the airport.

652
01:00:40,369 --> 01:00:41,563
Okay, I'll go.

653
01:00:41,729 --> 01:00:43,242
Dismissed.

654
01:00:50,889 --> 01:00:53,244
COSTA:
Oh, hey. Would you mind taking these?

655
01:00:53,889 --> 01:00:57,677
- We are running a little late.
- Yeah, I know. I know, I'm coming.

656
01:01:45,209 --> 01:01:47,279
Hi, James.

657
01:01:47,449 --> 01:01:48,677
Where you going?

658
01:01:50,449 --> 01:01:52,360
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

659
01:01:57,089 --> 01:01:58,920
Not leaving, are you?

660
01:02:00,609 --> 01:02:03,760
Come on, after all these fun games
we've been playing?

661
01:02:04,129 --> 01:02:06,848
All this time that I've put into it?

662
01:02:08,529 --> 01:02:10,087
Take a seat.

663
01:02:13,649 --> 01:02:16,447
There's a police officer
outside your apartment.

664
01:02:17,049 --> 01:02:21,520
I also couldn't help but notice
that you've been packing.

665
01:02:24,769 --> 01:02:26,282
And that...

666
01:02:26,449 --> 01:02:28,121
...is not...

667
01:02:28,809 --> 01:02:30,003
...okay!

668
01:02:34,089 --> 01:02:35,363
[CHOKING]

669
01:02:35,529 --> 01:02:38,441
Now, I thought you and I
had a special relationship.

670
01:02:39,329 --> 01:02:41,968
The kind that demanded
a great deal of respect.

671
01:02:42,129 --> 01:02:44,006
But obviously, you don't understand.

672
01:02:44,169 --> 01:02:46,125
So I'm gonna explain it to you again.

673
01:02:46,649 --> 01:02:50,324
You have something that I want.

674
01:02:50,489 --> 01:02:52,127
Therefore...

675
01:02:52,289 --> 01:02:54,359
...it's mine.

676
01:02:54,889 --> 01:02:57,005
So this idea of running away...

677
01:02:57,609 --> 01:02:58,883
...it's not gonna happen.

678
01:03:00,729 --> 01:03:02,799
I need you to answer something for me.

679
01:03:03,249 --> 01:03:05,763
What did you tell the police about me?

680
01:03:06,209 --> 01:03:07,847
What do the police know about...?

681
01:03:12,609 --> 01:03:14,406
[COUGHING]

682
01:03:29,529 --> 01:03:30,678
COSTA:
Help!

683
01:03:30,849 --> 01:03:32,441
Help me!

684
01:03:32,609 --> 01:03:34,645
Help!

685
01:03:42,809 --> 01:03:44,447
Drop it.

686
01:03:46,649 --> 01:03:48,082
I said, drop it!

687
01:03:54,689 --> 01:03:56,566
[GUN SHOOTING]

688
01:04:24,329 --> 01:04:27,924
This is Agent Scott.
Officer down, 219 St. Amelie.

689
01:04:31,849 --> 01:04:33,407
Shit.

690
01:04:34,369 --> 01:04:36,360
[TIRES SCREECHING]

691
01:05:27,849 --> 01:05:29,885
[HORNS HONKING]

692
01:06:13,009 --> 01:06:14,567
Help!

693
01:06:15,809 --> 01:06:17,208
[FABRIC TEARS]

694
01:06:22,329 --> 01:06:26,641
[GROANING]

695
01:06:28,489 --> 01:06:29,638
Is he dead?

696
01:06:31,529 --> 01:06:34,168
Is he dead? Is he dead?

697
01:06:35,049 --> 01:06:37,165
Help! Is he dead?

698
01:06:37,569 --> 01:06:39,764
ILLEANA: Drop your weapon!
- It's him. It's Asher!

699
01:06:39,929 --> 01:06:41,965
- Drop your weapon!
- He shot Duval.

700
01:06:44,329 --> 01:06:46,524
ILLEANA:
Move, move! Go!

701
01:07:17,769 --> 01:07:18,963
He was lucky.

702
01:07:19,329 --> 01:07:22,321
An accident like this, only stitches.

703
01:07:22,489 --> 01:07:24,923
Do you know where he was taking you,
Mr. Costa?

704
01:07:25,089 --> 01:07:26,238
I have no idea.

705
01:07:28,489 --> 01:07:31,481
I think he wanted to add Mr. Costa
to his collection.

706
01:07:33,369 --> 01:07:35,963
I'm so sorry about Inspector Duval.

707
01:07:36,369 --> 01:07:38,678
He was trying to save my life.

708
01:07:39,409 --> 01:07:42,287
- So, what now?
LECLAIR: We got our lab results.

709
01:07:42,569 --> 01:07:45,800
Asher's DNA matches the hairs
found on Clive Morin's body.

710
01:07:46,409 --> 01:07:48,445
So it's over?

711
01:07:49,369 --> 01:07:52,042
LECLAIR: I will need a statement
from you, some paperwork.

712
01:07:52,489 --> 01:07:55,561
Other than that, yeah, it's over.

713
01:07:56,769 --> 01:08:00,364
You did a very brave thing
in that car today, Mr. Costa.

714
01:08:03,369 --> 01:08:05,121
You were great.

715
01:08:05,849 --> 01:08:07,248
[STUTTERS]

716
01:08:07,689 --> 01:08:08,883
Thank you.

717
01:08:14,209 --> 01:08:15,562
Bye.

718
01:08:20,969 --> 01:08:22,448
[KNOCKS ON DOOR]

719
01:09:21,049 --> 01:09:23,040
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

720
01:09:23,689 --> 01:09:25,680
[MOANING]

721
01:10:06,289 --> 01:10:08,883
- May I help you?
- Call Ms. Scott's room, please.

722
01:10:09,049 --> 01:10:10,402
Of course.

723
01:10:14,009 --> 01:10:16,523
I'm so sorry, sir.
She has a "do not disturb."

724
01:10:16,689 --> 01:10:18,441
Can I take a message for her?

725
01:10:18,609 --> 01:10:20,122
No.

726
01:10:25,529 --> 01:10:27,326
[CHURCH BELLS RINGING]

727
01:11:17,049 --> 01:11:18,880
Hey. Hey.

728
01:11:19,289 --> 01:11:21,007
Hey.

729
01:11:21,169 --> 01:11:23,399
What? Ow.

730
01:11:24,969 --> 01:11:26,925
It's the stitches.

731
01:11:32,529 --> 01:11:35,089
Looks like you opened up some last night.

732
01:11:35,929 --> 01:11:38,238
I'll have to redo some of them.

733
01:11:46,569 --> 01:11:49,959
- They got art down there, don't they?
- What?

734
01:11:50,289 --> 01:11:52,359
Down there in Washington, D.C.

735
01:11:52,529 --> 01:11:56,568
Those politician types, they like to hang
things on their walls, don't they?

736
01:11:56,729 --> 01:11:59,243
I'm just saying, I could start a little...

737
01:11:59,569 --> 01:12:03,244
You know, a gallery.

738
01:12:03,729 --> 01:12:06,289
I could find a space there.

